Here are Some Interesting Facts about McLaren GT The first McLaren car was the now-legendary McLaren Fl. The car was launched in 1992 and it set the ground for what the automaker produced in the future using its race car technology and knowledge. F1 also set a new record of being the fastest production car in the world. To date, the car is viewed as one of the greatest road cars produced, comprising of a V12 engine churning out 618-horsepower and 3.2-second 0-96-km/h time, suspension design and carbon monocoque chassis. McLaren was founded by a professional motor racer, Bruce McLaren. Bruce won his first motor race at the age of 13 and at 21, he won the American Grand Prix. McLaren won the Can-Am title in 1967 and 1969, and his teammate Denny Hulme won the title in 1968. Bruce also lost his life at CanAm at the age of just 32. In 1970, the innovative racing professional car racer lost his life on the Goodwood Circuit in the UK as he was testing McLaren M8D a Can-Am prototype car. The first logo of McLaren was designed by artist Michael Turner. The logo consists of a Kiwi bird in the centre and the company name at the top. The usage of the Kiwi bird represents the connection of Bruce McLaren with his birthplace, New Zealand. However, when McLaren became a globalised brand the old logo was replaced with the current one. McLaren is an eco-friendly brand and takes precautions for reducing the carbon footprint of its vehicles. Around 60% of the total waste generated by the company is recycled. In fact, McLaren also unveiled a plug-in hybrid Pl model. It contains electric motors paired with a 3.6-Litre twin-turbocharged V8 engine that can create a total of 903 hp.
